    "response_text": "The cumulative number of livestock destocked across households begins at zero and rises consistently throughout the simulation, reaching approximately 97 animals per household by year 100. Early in the simulation (years 0\u201325), the accumulation occurs most rapidly, with the steepest rates of increase observed in the first decade as households adjust initial stocking levels of 90 animals to actual carrying capacity under highly variable rainfall conditions. This initial phase suggests intensive correction of overstocking as farmers encounter the reality of pasture limitations.\n\nAround year 25, the rate of accumulation slows markedly, indicating a transition from shock adjustments to more sustained management patterns. The growth continues to decelerate through the middle decades, settling into a slower but steady increase characterized by oscillations with a dominant period of approximately 49 years. These cyclical patterns appear between years 20\u201325 and again around years 50\u201360, suggesting multi-decadal rhythms likely linked to vegetation recovery cycles or extended rainfall variability affecting pasture productivity.\n\nInflection points clustered around years 45\u201347 and 53\u201357 indicate shifts in the acceleration of destocking rates, while a change point at year 60 marks further stabilization in the accumulation pattern. By the final decades (60\u2013100), the metric proceeds at a reduced but persistent pace with minimal additional deceleration, suggesting the system approaches a steady-state where destocking becomes part of regular adaptive management rather than crisis response.\n\nThe magnitude of cumulative destocking\u2014exceeding initial herd sizes over the century\u2014implies multiple restocking and destocking cycles as households adapt to ecological variability. The declining rate of accumulation over time suggests that learning strategies enable farmers to reduce the severity or frequency of destocking events as they accumulate experience, though they cannot eliminate them entirely.\n\nFor decision makers, the concentration of destocking activity in the first 25 years highlights the critical importance of early support mechanisms for new entrants to grazing systems. The persistence of destocking needs throughout the century, despite learning, indicates that even experienced managers require frameworks capable of handling multi-decadal climatic cycles, and that stocking decisions under high rainfall variability necessitate ongoing adaptive capacity regardless of the specific learning approach employed."

